                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.2325/27: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moore</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-07-28T11:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 28, 1928—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 1:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. When your 62, July 21, 1 p.m., was brought to the attention of President
                    Leguia yesterday he said that he saw no reason why Chile should not go ahead
                    with the procedure mentioned therein.</p>
                <p>[Paraphrase.] The President was gratified by this indication of good will on
                    Chile’s part and added hopefully these words: “We will see how far she is
                    willing to go.” [End paraphrase.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
